segments.text: Basically, the curriculum follows the generalist with a specialty model, which originally was described by Harvey Perloff.
So that was never really changed.
So there's always been a fairly large core
seven or eight courses.
And then maybe about five specialty areas that students are supposed to pick from the, I think they take like four courses in each one.
And some of the content of these changed.
With the curriculum review there was some change.
Now they may have made some substantial changes since I left.
I'm not real up to date on it.
The program is very heavy in quantitative methods.
Terry Kahn teaches two semester sequence, which is required.
And then I taught a course in more applied methods, which really dealt with things like population and economic forecasting.
Terry's courses were pretty strictly statistics and calculus and linear programming.
And he's a very popular teacher.
So those actually, many years, those got the highest evaluations of all the courses in the curriculum.
And then Terry, while I was there, Dean Box started a teaching award, teaching prize.
And I guess the last year I was there, I think in 81, Terry got the teaching award for the School of Architecture, which I think Dean Box got $1,000 cash.
award to go with it.
He always seemed to be able to get money.
We want to give $500 every year for this.
Will you sign up to do it for the rest of your life?
So I think that's true.
And then I remember the change.
We put in an economics course.
We made that required.
And Sandy Rosenblum had been teaching that for several years.
There's not really a lot of theory in it.
You don't have a theory course?
Well, we had an urban and regional theory course.
Who taught that?
I taught it for about two years.
I kind of taught regional economics.
But then Pat Salinas-Wilson taught it.
And she's a radical planner.
And she used kind of Marxist-type material and all.
So she did a quite different thing.
Neither is taught as a quantitative course.
So it's not really a regional science type course.
If you consider regional science to be mathematically oriented, which they of course do at the Association of Regional Scientists.
Yeah, they say Tom Reiner is famous as the only non-quantitative regional scientist.
Yeah.
Well, okay, so you had, and then what did Peter Koltman teach?
Well, Peter, let's see, when I, he had kind of his own group of courses when, when I arrived there, the several were environmental planning area, and they were kind of Ian McHarr type courses.
They were landscape analysis, and then he had,
I think one in English planning and one in New Towns, something kind of based upon some of his own experience, which I guess maybe some of it was in South Africa, maybe some in Great Britain.
You'd have to kind of tell me about that.
And those, apparently one time, those were quite popular.
But at the time I arrived there, the enrollment got very low in those courses, and people weren't interested in New Towns anymore.
And so his courses had changed quite a bit.
And eventually, he put in a studio, a two semester studio as a terminal option.
And he taught that course.
And he was doing that when I left him.
Originally, everybody had to do a thesis.
And they had the same problem.
that half the people never finished.
So then they put in a professional report, which was supposed to be an easier version.
And I think it only gave three hours credit.
And that helped a little, but there's still a third of the students were never finishing.
That's what we have now.
Well, it's not too bad.
So we finally decided to put in a third option, which was to take a studio course, because there had never been a required studio in the time I was there.
That's interesting, because A&M was always- For so many years, there wasn't a single studio course.
A&M was always required, too.
Yeah.
Okay, so Peter Coleman had been teaching that studio course for a while.
And also he taught, I think, an undergraduate architecture course.
They were always trying to make sure that each of the specialties had a qualified person in it.
And that was always important in picking the faculty.
And transportation planning was always one of the specialties.
And that was one reason why they hired me.
Sandy Rosenblum also teaches in transportation, but she's non-quantitative, basically non-technical.
She has a PhD in political science from UCLA.
And so her courses are very policy-oriented, and they deal with legal background and social issues.
So she's always taught at least one transportation course, which
particularly interest.
Paratransit is one.
She's one of the leading experts on taxis in the country.
And she's dealt a lot of transportation to the elderly and handicapped.
I taught the more technical and quantitative transportation courses.
There was also an option in environmental planning.
And we finally decided that Peter Coleman really didn't have a kind of background.
To do that adequately, he didn't really have any biology background, any natural science.
So we went out specifically looking for someone while I was there, and we hired Ken Butler.
He came from Wisconsin.
I thought he was an outstanding faculty member.
He developed like four new courses.
and environmental planning that we'd never had before.
There was a policy course.
There were technical courses.
He did one in coastal zone management, which I think he finally had a job because the federal government killed the program and it became irrelevant.
But he did that.
And he worked in Galveston and Corpus Christi and some of those places.
He did some consulting on that.
And he, after I left, he got tenure.
And then Gus went with the lower Colorado River Authority, whatever.
I don't know what's happened to him.
He's still there.
He's still there, I think.
We also had Maureen McReynolds sometimes taught a course, who was the City of Austin's Director of Environmental Management.
They always had...
A few practitioners that would teach.
Sometimes if there was a temporary vacancy, we'd bring in practitioners.
Dick Lilly was taught regularly for all the time I was there.
First one course a year, and then later a course every semester.
What did he teach?
He taught a, it was kind of a course in the master plan.
Basically, I think that was the course he taught every year was I think they basically went through the process of how to prepare a master plan.
That sort of leads into this discussion with the relationship between architecture and planning.
Since the planning faculty at Texas
you know, went to a lot of lengths to distance themselves from old-fashioned physical planning.
And the same thing is going on in Kansas, too.
And I guess many schools... Well, it happened in Berkeley for a while.
Yes.
Well, it's probably still going on.
I don't know if it's resolved or complex or not.
So, part of this...
manifested itself in Austin and basically this huge division between the architecture faculty and the planning faculty.
They kind of ignored each other.
And while I was there, we were in different buildings.
The planning faculty was all in Sutton Hall.
Most of the architecture faculty were in the old building, which I think now is called Goldsmith Hall.
And certainly the dean's office was in Goldsmith Hall, so we never saw him.
And I guess that Peter Colvin was in kind of an awkward position because he was one of the old fashioned types and he was sort of caught in the middle and wasn't really successful as a bridge.
Also a lot of it had to do with trying to get away from the image of Hugo Leipziger Pierce.
And these people that were there when I was there,
felt that he had given a very bad image to the planning program in Austin.
And they wanted to make sure everybody was different.
Now, I don't know enough about what went on, but I understand Hugo kind of promoted the 701 program throughout the state of Texas.
And I think he had a huge collection of 701 master plans that he gave to the library in Austin and all.
But as I said, some of the younger people who came along, they kind of emphasized there was a social science type curriculum.
You would call it a word curriculum.
I don't know how to say that, because they emphasize the quantitative methods a lot, too.
So it's words and numbers, but not much drawing.
So there's very little of that.
We'll try to change that back some.
It's not a matter of drawing, though.
My point is not that.
It's a matter of that.
sooner or later, decision makers are going to have to make vocational choices.
And they can't do it on the basis of simply a lot of policies.
They've got to have something a bit more definitive than that.
And I think that that's Jack Kent's point, too.
The problem with Jack Kent, as I see it, is he forgets the social and economic inputs to it, pretty much.
Not entirely.
very interested in drawing a firm boundary.
I never agreed with him on that.
In fact, even back in 1958, 59, most of the students disagreed with him.
Yeah.
Well, he knows I do, too, and we're having problems.
I thought Jack was very fair that you could write an essay that took the opposite position from Jack's.
If you thought it was a good essay, he'd give you an A.
He didn't insist the students agreed with him.
Well, he's changing a little bit.
Well, let me, let's see, get back to Texas and let's see.
Well, yeah, the organization is a little strange because the planning program doesn't really fit in anywhere.
Basically, there's a school of architecture.
There is no department of architecture.
There's no program in architecture.
And actually, Hal Box is the head of architecture.
But then there is this other little thing, which is the community planning program.
It's a program.
It's a program.
And it doesn't have control of its own budget, does it?
No, it doesn't.
That's controlled out of the dean's office.
Yes, it's done out of the dean's office.
So you don't really have a department head.
Terry Kahn does not function as a department head.
No, he's not a department head.
He's a program director?
Yes, I think that's right.
Now, this is not unusual, not to have all this autonomy.
But basically, they're in a completely anomalous position.
They're just an oddity.
And you see here in Kansas right now, we don't have departments.
We're in a college of architecture.
There are three programs.
There's planning, there's architecture, and there's architectural engineering.
But we're equal.
We each have our own director, or I guess it's called chair now, and we each have the same limitations with regard to autonomy.
But that's not true in Texas.
You see, architecture...
is it, except there's this little, you know, little boil on the surface of the skin of the program, which is planning, and it just doesn't fit in anywhere.
Yeah.
So you're always sort of a stepchild.
Yeah.
And I don't know, I think the accreditation visit came up after I left, and you say this was a source of problems.
I can believe that's true.
I understand from faculty at UT Arlington that they do not expect to be reaccredited.
Either Austin doesn't or Arlington doesn't?
Arlington.
Arlington is quite small.
It might not have enough faculty.
Well, I think it has to do with resources and with administrative structure, too.
So anyway,
We always complain at A&M about things, but by comparison, I guess that our structure is extremely clear.
Well, that's really pretty hazy.
And Hal Box never went to graduate school.
He just has a Bachelor of Architecture and then went into practice.
So he has always had a lot of trouble understanding what planning was doing.
And I don't think he understands too much what goes on in graduate school.
So OK, well, Terry Kahn never studied planning.
But he is from Texas.
And I think got his bachelor's and master's in the business school of Texas.
And then went to Berkeley and got a PhD.
And was involved in the real estate program at Berkeley.
And basically, he knows a lot about real estate and teaches courses that deal with that.
He's very loyal to the private sector.
He probably studied under Paul Wendt in the real estate research.
That's quite possible.
But he was always kind of a specialist in quantitative methods.
So while his degree says something like land economics or real estate, he was almost really a student of quantitative methods.
So he teaches, as I say, both those methods courses, which are very popular.
And then his other courses usually have to do with land use, but tend to be not from the regulatory viewpoint, but from the developer viewpoint.
A lot of students are interested in that.
I mean, we always had quite a few students who were going into planning because they wanted to become millionaires.
I don't know how it is at A&M.
Well, we have a new degree, the Master of Science in Land Development.
Which takes care of that.
Formally recognized it.
Yeah, it's a specialty master of science degree.
I want to ask you, at UT Austin, are the students required to have an internship?
No.
I don't think very many schools require that because they can't place the students.
We do.
You do require them?
Oh, yes.
Well, do they get paid for the internships?
Yes, they get paid about $1,200 a month.
No, I think most programs gave that up when it became hard to find jobs.
So they don't.
They did give some academic credit for people who worked.
They gave up to nine hours, even.
Oh, we only give two.
The only exceptions to that are some of our international students.
who would not benefit by American practice or would have trouble finding an internship because they're not citizens.
McClure came along, and his own particular specialty was planning law.
We didn't really have anybody to teach that before.
But when we changed the curriculum, we made that a required course.
Of course, everybody likes to have their subject required.
And he apparently did very well in that.
He knew the subject very thoroughly.
Then he also taught an elective seminar in growth management.
So that was kind of the area that he went in for a while.
All right.
Well, let me talk about the students a little bit.
There are a lot of very good students at Austin.
And there are a lot of people who want to come to Texas, of course.
And a lot of them particularly want to come to Austin.
So they probably get better students than they deserve to have.
They have a lot of people with Ivy League degrees, and people from the Big Ten, and Pacific Coast schools, and so forth.
Not a whole lot of foreign students.
That was fairly small.
Probably the best student I ever had there was an Italian student, including
He's English, which is very good.
Most of the applicants are from Texas.
I would say at least half of the people are living in Austin already at the time they applied the program.
A lot of them are Northeasterners or Midwesterners who have come down there and lived in Austin for a year or two and decided to go to graduate school.
There are also a lot of other applications from around Texas.
I would say at least two-thirds of the applications are from Texas.
And the others are all kind of scattered.
There are quite a few from Southern California, I think.
There seem to be quite a few students.
Where do they go after they get their degrees?
Well, of course, they go all over.
But the majority of them work in Texas.
It seems like that most of them want to stay in Austin.
I mean, almost everybody loves Austin.
And all the agencies in Austin have quite a few of them there.
But they're kind of scattered around Texas.
I guess there are a few in the Houston area.
I think there are probably more in the Dallas-Fort Worth area.
But some of them go all around the country, too.
Do they generally take government-type planning jobs or in the private sector?
Or how does it fall?
I think there's more interest in the private sector than in most planning schools.
As I say, there are quite a few that are money-oriented.
There are some whose fathers are developers.
And we've had some, according to rumor, some of the students, their fathers were worth tens of millions of dollars.
all made in land use development.
Well, I hope they still have it with the turndown.
Yeah, I don't know about that.
So I would say that the majority do go into the public sector jobs.
But I think there's probably a larger number that are interested in the private sector than in the typical planning program.
There's one question I have to ask about the program in closing.
And that is, I have heard it rumored
that there is no history of planning course at the University of Texas at Austin.
No, I don't think so.
You mean a whole course in the history of planning?
No, there's no course like that.
Shocking.
I don't think, most programs, we don't have a course like that at Kansas either.
Shocking.
Well, I can come up and teach it.
Well, of course.
A fellow at Ohio State is doing that on a contract basis.
Yeah, Larry Gerkins.
Larry Gerkins, right.
He's very good.
Yes, he came out to Kansas City last fall.
Yeah, he's excellent.
Okay.
Some of the students have done very well.
I guess Sally Shipman is one of the most successful students.
It happened...
I guess about... Sally Shipman is currently a city council person in Austin.

It happens about, I think it was about four years ago, I was nominated to run for the National Board of Directors of APA, and when I asked, I guess Ed Stolman called me up, and I asked who was running against me, and they said, well, some woman I don't know named Sally Shipman.
Both from the same city.
No, I was living in Kansas.
Oh, you were in Kansas at that time.
I was in Kansas, and he didn't know her.
And the lawyer said, that was one of my students.
She was on her thesis committee.
Well, she won very handily in that.
There was a time when there was a lot of conflict, and there was a petition candidate, too.
But she won that election.
So she's quite well known nationally, too.
Ellen.
want to thank you for your time and for your very valuable input to this project.
I'm sure it will make it far more richer and more accurate and more interesting.
All right.
Glad to do that.
Thank you.
